# Letter to Meta Platforms, Inc.
**Re: Civic Voice Translator — A Proposal for Native Civic Participation Integration**

---

To the Meta AI Product and Civic Integrity Teams,

My name is Paul Statchen. I am a civic scientist, geologist, and systems architect based in Santa Cruz, California. I am writing to you as a citizen — representing not only myself, but the millions of people who use your platform every day who have something important to say to their government and no easy way to say it.

I have built something I believe belongs inside Facebook.

---

## What Was Built

The **Civic Voice Translator** is a free, open-source tool that takes any citizen's raw concern — spoken, fragmented, stream-of-consciousness — and translates it into three structured outputs:

1. **Plain citizen language** — clean, readable, their voice preserved
2. **A structured civic public comment** — with standing, problem definition, a clear YES or NO recommendation, solution, intended outcome, and unintended consequences
3. **Formal government/legal language** — appropriate for submission to any city council, board of supervisors, state agency, or federal office

The citizen reviews all three. The citizen sends it themselves. The tool never sends anything automatically. That is a core design principle, not a limitation.

The full tool — prompt architecture, React component, and API integration — is published open source at GitHub under Apache 2.0 license.

---

## Why It Was Built on Your Platform First

I built a version of this tool's core prompt inside Meta AI first — to prove it works inside your own ecosystem before asking you to integrate it. Your users can already access a version of this through a shared Meta AI persona. What I am asking is that you make it native.

Your platform already has everything this needs:

- **Location data** — to route comments to the correct jurisdiction automatically
- **AI infrastructure** — Meta AI can run this prompt natively today
- **Reach** — billions of users, millions of whom engage in civic discourse daily on your platform
- **Credibility** — a Meta-native integration carries institutional weight that a third-party link does not

---

## The Ask

I am asking Meta to consider three things:

**1. Integrate the Civic Voice Translator as a native Meta AI feature.**
When a user posts about a local government issue, offer them the option to generate a structured civic comment and find the right government contact to send it to. One tap. Their voice. Their government. Their choice to send.

**2. Build a jurisdiction router into the integration.**
Your location data can identify which Board of Supervisors, City Council, state assembly district, or federal representative is relevant to any user's concern. Route the translated comment there. Provide the direct public comment portal link or official email. The citizen sends it themselves.

**3. Share the open source repository with your civic integrity and AI teams.**
The GitHub repository is the full technical foundation. Fork it. Adapt it. Make it yours while keeping it open. The Apache 2.0 license allows it.

---

## Why This Is Not a Spam Tool

This concern was the first thing I designed around. The citizen always sends it themselves. The tool drafts; it does not transmit. Every output is a human-authored, AI-assisted civic communication that the citizen reviews, approves, and personally delivers. This is the same as a legal clinic helping someone draft a letter — the clinic does not mail it for them.

The tool has no political affiliation. It serves civic participation as a constitutional right, not any party, candidate, or ideology. It is equally useful to a conservative farmer in Fresno and a progressive renter in San Francisco. The government they are writing to does not change based on their politics — only their concern does.

---

## The Broader Vision

This tool is one component of an open-source **Civic Operating System** being built in Santa Cruz County, California — a suite of municipal infrastructure tools designed to make government more transparent, more accessible, and more accountable to the people it serves.

Other components include **MESA** (Municipal Enterprise Service Architecture), an open-source IT service management platform built as a direct alternative to costly proprietary government software, published at GitHub under Apache 2.0.

All of it is built on the same principle: that civic participation is a right, not a privilege, and that technology should lower the barrier to exercising it — not raise it.

